<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Menstrual Disorders</h2>
    
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Painful Periods (Dysmenorrhea)</h4>
            <p><strong>Description:</strong> Severe, frequent cramping and pain during menstruation that interferes with daily activities.</p>
            <h5>Types:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Primary:</strong> Pain without an underlying condition, begins with first periods</li>
              <li><strong>Secondary:</strong> Pain caused by a disorder in the reproductive organs</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Symptoms:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Lower abdominal cramping</li>
              <li>Pain radiating to lower back and thighs</li>
              <li>Nausea and vomiting</li>
              <li>Diarrhea</li>
              <li>Headache</li>
              <li>Fatigue</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Treatment Options:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>NSAIDs (ibuprofen, naproxen sodium)</li>
              <li>Hormonal birth control</li>
              <li>Heat therapy</li>
              <li>Exercise</li>
              <li>Dietary changes</li>
              <li>Treatment of underlying conditions (for secondary dysmenorrhea)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Heavy Menstrual Bleeding (Menorrhagia)</h4>
            <p><strong>Description:</strong> Abnormally heavy or prolonged menstrual bleeding.</p>
            <h5>Signs of Heavy Bleeding:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Soaking through one or more pads/tampons every hour</li>
              <li>Needing to use double sanitary protection</li>
              <li>Needing to change protection during the night</li>
              <li>Bleeding for more than 7 days</li>
              <li>Passing large blood clots</li>
              <li>Symptoms of anemia (fatigue, weakness)</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Possible Causes:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Hormonal imbalance</li>
              <li>Uterine fibroids</li>
              <li>Polyps</li>
              <li>Adenomyosis</li>
              <li>IUD use</li>
              <li>Medications (anticoagulants)</li>
              <li>Blood disorders</li>
              <li>Cancer (rarely)</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Treatment Options:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Hormonal treatments (birth control pills, IUD)</li>
              <li>Non-hormonal medications (tranexamic acid, NSAIDs)</li>
              <li>Iron supplements (for anemia)</li>
              <li>Surgical procedures (endometrial ablation, myomectomy)</li>
              <li>Hysterectomy (for severe cases unresponsive to other treatments)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Irregular Periods</h4>
            <p><strong>Description:</strong> Menstrual cycles that are unpredictable in timing, with varying lengths between periods.</p>
            <h5>What's Considered Irregular:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Cycles shorter than 21 days or longer than 35 days</li>
              <li>Variations of more than 7-9 days between cycles</li>
              <li>Missing three or more periods in a row</li>
              <li>Bleeding between periods</li>
              <li>Bleeding after sex</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Possible Causes:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS)</li>
              <li>Thyroid disorders</li>
              <li>Uncontrolled diabetes</li>
              <li>Eating disorders or extreme weight loss</li>
              <li>Excessive exercise</li>
              <li>Stress</li>
              <li>Perimenopause</li>
              <li>Certain medications</li>
              <li>Uterine or cervical cancer (rarely)</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Treatment Options:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Treatment of underlying condition</li>
              <li>Hormonal birth control</li>
              <li>Lifestyle modifications</li>
              <li>Stress management</li>
              <li>Maintaining healthy weight</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" style="background-color: var(--light-color);">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Reproductive System Conditions</h2>
    
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Endometriosis</h4>
            <p><strong>Description:</strong> A condition where tissue similar to the uterine lining grows outside the uterus, most commonly on the ovaries, fallopian tubes, and pelvic tissues.</p>
            <h5>Symptoms:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Severe menstrual cramps</li>
              <li>Pain during or after sex</li>
              <li>Pain with bowel movements or urination (especially during periods)</li>
              <li>Excessive bleeding</li>
              <li>Infertility</li>
              <li>Fatigue, diarrhea, constipation, bloating or nausea (especially during periods)</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Risk Factors:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Family history</li>
              <li>Starting periods at an early age</li>
              <li>Short menstrual cycles</li>
              <li>Heavy menstrual periods lasting more than 7 days</li>
              <li>Never having given birth</li>
              <li>Low body mass index</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Treatment Options:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Pain medications</li>
              <li>Hormonal treatments (birth control pills, IUD, GnRH agonists)</li>
              <li>Conservative surgery (laparoscopy to remove endometrial tissue)</li>
              <li>Hysterectomy with removal of ovaries (for severe cases)</li>
              <li>Fertility treatment (if trying to conceive)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)</h4>
            <p><strong>Description:</strong> A hormonal disorder causing enlarged ovaries with small cysts, irregular periods, and excess male hormone levels.</p>
            <h5>Symptoms:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Irregular periods or no periods</li>
              <li>Heavy bleeding</li>
              <li>Excess facial and body hair</li>
              <li>Acne</li>
              <li>Male-pattern baldness</li>
              <li>Weight gain and difficulty losing weight</li>
              <li>Darkening of skin (especially in neck creases, groin, underneath breasts)</li>
              <li>Headaches</li>
              <li>Fertility problems</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Complications:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Infertility</li>
              <li>Gestational diabetes or pregnancy-induced high blood pressure</li>
              <li>Metabolic syndrome</li>
              <li>Type 2 diabetes</li>
              <li>Depression and anxiety</li>
              <li>Sleep apnea</li>
              <li>Endometrial cancer</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Treatment Options:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Lifestyle changes (weight loss, healthy diet, exercise)</li>
              <li>Birth control pills to regulate periods</li>
              <li>Anti-androgen medications</li>
              <li>Metformin (to improve insulin resistance)</li>
              <li>Fertility medications (if trying to conceive)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Uterine Fibroids</h4>
            <p><strong>Description:</strong> Noncancerous growths in or on the uterus, ranging from tiny seedlings to bulky masses that can distort the uterus.</p>
            <h5>Symptoms:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Heavy menstrual bleeding</li>
              <li>Prolonged periods</li>
              <li>Pelvic pressure or pain</li>
              <li>Frequent urination</li>
              <li>Difficulty emptying bladder</li>
              <li>Constipation</li>
              <li>Backache or leg pain</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Risk Factors:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Age (develop during childbearing years)</li>
              <li>Family history</li>
              <li>African heritage</li>
              <li>Obesity</li>
              <li>Early onset of menstruation</li>
              <li>Vitamin D deficiency</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Treatment Options:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Watchful waiting (if symptoms are minimal)</li>
              <li>Medications to regulate hormones and reduce bleeding</li>
              <li>Noninvasive procedures (MRI-guided focused ultrasound)</li>
              <li>Minimally invasive procedures (uterine artery embolization, myolysis)</li>
              <li>Traditional surgical options (myomectomy, hysterectomy)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Ovarian Cysts</h4>
            <p><strong>Description:</strong> Fluid-filled sacs that develop on or inside the ovaries.</p>
            <h5>Types:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Functional cysts:</strong> Normal part of menstrual cycle, usually harmless and resolve on their own</li>
              <li><strong>Pathological cysts:</strong> Not related to normal function, less common but may require treatment</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Symptoms:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Often asymptomatic</li>
              <li>Pelvic pain or pressure</li>
              <li>Bloating or swelling</li>
              <li>Pain during sex</li>
              <li>Changes in menstrual patterns</li>
              <li>Sudden, severe abdominal pain (if cyst ruptures)</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>When to Seek Medical Attention:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Sudden, severe abdominal or pelvic pain</li>
              <li>Pain with fever or vomiting</li>
              <li>Signs of shock (cold, clammy skin, rapid breathing, lightheadedness)</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Treatment Options:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Watchful waiting for functional cysts</li>
              <li>Hormonal contraceptives to prevent new cysts</li>
              <li>Surgery (laparoscopy or laparotomy) for persistent, large, or painful cysts</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Infections and Inflammation</h2>
    
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Yeast Infections</h4>
            <p><strong>Description:</strong> Fungal infection caused by overgrowth of Candida, usually in the vagina.</p>
            <h5>Symptoms:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Itching and irritation in the vagina and vulva</li>
              <li>Burning sensation, especially during urination or intercourse</li>
              <li>Redness and swelling of the vulva</li>
              <li>Vaginal pain and soreness</li>
              <li>Thick, white, odorless discharge with "cottage cheese" appearance</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Risk Factors:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Antibiotics (which kill beneficial bacteria)</li>
              <li>Increased estrogen levels (pregnancy, hormone therapy)</li>
              <li>Uncontrolled diabetes</li>
              <li>Compromised immune system</li>
              <li>Sexual activity</li>
              <li>Tight-fitting, non-cotton underwear</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Treatment Options:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Over-the-counter antifungal creams, ointments, or suppositories</li>
              <li>Prescription-strength antifungals</li>
              <li>Single-dose oral medication for severe infections</li>
              <li>Boric acid capsules for recurring infections</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Prevention:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Wear cotton underwear</li>
              <li>Avoid douching</li>
              <li>Change out of wet clothes promptly</li>
              <li>Maintain good hygiene</li>
              <li>Consider probiotics</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Bacterial Vaginosis (BV)</h4>
            <p><strong>Description:</strong> Imbalance of naturally occurring bacteria in the vagina.</p>
            <h5>Symptoms:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Thin grayish-white discharge</li>
              <li>Fish-like odor, especially after sex</li>
              <li>Burning during urination</li>
              <li>Itching around the vagina</li>
              <li>Many women have no symptoms</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Risk Factors:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Multiple or new sexual partners</li>
              <li>Douching</li>
              <li>Lack of condom use</li>
              <li>Natural lack of lactobacilli bacteria</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Treatment Options:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Antibiotics (oral or vaginal)</li>
              <li>Probiotics (as complementary therapy)</li>
              <li>Avoiding triggers</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Complications if Untreated:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Increased risk of STIs</li>
              <li>Pregnancy complications</li>
              <li>Post-surgical infections</li>
              <li>Pelvic inflammatory disease (rarely)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Pelvic Inflammatory Disease (PID)</h4>
            <p><strong>Description:</strong> Infection of the female reproductive organs, typically caused by bacteria spreading from the vagina to the uterus, fallopian tubes, or ovaries.</p>
            <h5>Symptoms:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Lower abdominal pain</li>
              <li>Fever</li>
              <li>Unusual vaginal discharge with bad odor</li>
              <li>Pain or bleeding during sex</li>
              <li>Burning during urination</li>
              <li>Bleeding between periods</li>
              <li>Some women have mild or no symptoms</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Risk Factors:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Sexually transmitted infections (especially gonorrhea and chlamydia)</li>
              <li>Multiple sexual partners</li>
              <li>Previous PID</li>
              <li>Young age (sexually active teens)</li>
              <li>Douching</li>
              <li>IUD insertion (risk is primarily in the first 3 weeks)</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Treatment Options:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Antibiotics</li>
              <li>Hospitalization for severe cases or pregnancy</li>
              <li>Surgical intervention for abscesses</li>
              <li>Treatment of sexual partners</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Complications if Untreated:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Infertility</li>
              <li>Ectopic pregnancy</li>
              <li>Chronic pelvic pain</li>
              <li>Tubo-ovarian abscess</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" style="background-color: var(--light-color);">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Pelvic Floor Disorders</h2>
    
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Urinary Incontinence</h4>
            <p><strong>Description:</strong> Involuntary leakage of urine, ranging from occasional minor leaks to complete inability to control urination.</p>
            <h5>Types:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Stress incontinence:</strong> Leakage with pressure on bladder (coughing, sneezing, exercise)</li>
              <li><strong>Urge incontinence:</strong> Sudden, intense urge followed by involuntary loss of urine</li>
              <li><strong>Overflow incontinence:</strong> Frequent or constant dribbling due to bladder not emptying completely</li>
              <li><strong>Mixed incontinence:</strong> Combination of stress and urge incontinence</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Risk Factors:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Age</li>
              <li>Pregnancy and childbirth</li>
              <li>Menopause</li>
              <li>Hysterectomy</li>
              <li>Obesity</li>
              <li>Urinary tract infections</li>
              <li>Neurological disorders</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Treatment Options:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Pelvic floor exercises (Kegels)</li>
              <li>Bladder training</li>
              <li>Lifestyle changes (weight loss, dietary changes)</li>
              <li>Medications</li>
              <li>Devices (pessary, urethral insert)</li>
              <li>Electrical stimulation therapy</li>
              <li>Surgery for severe cases</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Pelvic Organ Prolapse</h4>
            <p><strong>Description:</strong> Condition where one or more pelvic organs (uterus, bladder, rectum) drop from their normal position and press against the vaginal walls.</p>
            <h5>Types:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Uterine prolapse:</strong> Uterus descends into the vagina</li>
              <li><strong>Cystocele:</strong> Bladder bulges into the front vaginal wall</li>
              <li><strong>Rectocele:</strong> Rectum bulges into the back vaginal wall</li>
              <li><strong>Enterocele:</strong> Small intestine bulges into the vagina</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Symptoms:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Sensation of heaviness or pulling in the pelvis</li>
              <li>Tissue protruding from the vagina</li>
              <li>Urinary or fecal incontinence</li>
              <li>Difficulty emptying bladder or bowels</li>
              <li>Sexual difficulties</li>
              <li>Lower back pain</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Risk Factors:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Vaginal childbirth</li>
              <li>Age and menopause</li>
              <li>Hysterectomy</li>
              <li>Obesity</li>
              <li>Chronic constipation or coughing</li>
              <li>Repetitive heavy lifting</li>
              <li>Genetic factors</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Treatment Options:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Pelvic floor exercises</li>
              <li>Pessary (supportive device inserted into vagina)</li>
              <li>Estrogen therapy</li>
              <li>Lifestyle changes (weight loss, avoiding heavy lifting)</li>
              <li>Surgery</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Prevention and Wellness</h2>
    
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-md-6">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Preventive Measures</h4>
            <h5>Regular Screenings and Check-ups:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Annual gynecological exams</li>
              <li>Pap smears (frequency based on age and history)</li>
              <li>STI testing</li>
              <li>Mammograms (typically beginning at age 40-50)</li>
              <li>Bone density tests (postmenopausal women)</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Sexual Health Practices:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Practice safe sex (condoms, dental dams)</li>
              <li>Limit number of sexual partners</li>
              <li>Get vaccinated against HPV</li>
              <li>Get tested regularly for STIs if sexually active</li>
              <li>Communicate openly with partners about sexual health</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Good Hygiene Practices:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Wipe from front to back after using the toilet</li>
              <li>Change tampons and pads regularly during menstruation</li>
              <li>Avoid douching and feminine deodorant sprays</li>
              <li>Wear cotton underwear</li>
              <li>Avoid tight-fitting pants for extended periods</li>
              <li>Change out of wet clothing promptly</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Lifestyle for Gynecological Health</h4>
            <h5>Nutrition:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Maintain a balanced diet rich in fruits, vegetables, and whole grains</li>
              <li>Ensure adequate calcium and vitamin D for bone health</li>
              <li>Stay hydrated</li>
              <li>Consider foods rich in omega-3 fatty acids to help reduce inflammation</li>
              <li>Limit alcohol consumption</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Physical Activity:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Engage in regular moderate exercise</li>
              <li>Incorporate strength training for bone health</li>
              <li>Practice pelvic floor exercises</li>
              <li>Consider yoga or pilates for core strength</li>
              <li>Maintain a healthy weight</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Stress Management:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Practice relaxation techniques</li>
              <li>Ensure adequate sleep</li>
              <li>Consider mindfulness or meditation</li>
              <li>Seek social support</li>
              <li>Manage chronic stress, which can affect hormonal balance</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Harmful Habits to Avoid:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Smoking (increases risk of cervical cancer and earlier menopause)</li>
              <li>Excessive alcohol consumption</li>
              <li>Prolonged use of certain medications without medical supervision</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" style="background-color: var(--light-color);">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="text-center mb-4">When to See a Healthcare Provider</h2>
    
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-lg-10 mx-auto">
        <div class="alert alert-info">
          <p>While many minor gynecological symptoms may resolve on their own, certain signs warrant prompt medical attention.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="card mb-4">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Seek Medical Care If You Experience:</h4>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="col-md-6">
                <ul>
                  <li>Severe pelvic pain, especially if sudden</li>
                  <li>Abnormal vaginal bleeding (heavy, prolonged, after menopause, or between periods)</li>
                  <li>Missed periods (if sexually active and pregnancy is possible)</li>
                  <li>Unusual vaginal discharge with strong odor, unusual color, or accompanied by itching</li>
                  <li>Pain or bleeding during or after sex</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="col-md-6">
                <ul>
                  <li>Painful urination or bowel movements</li>
                  <li>Persistent bloating or abdominal swelling</li>
                  <li>Sores, bumps, blisters, or rashes in the genital area</li>
                  <li>Breast changes (lumps, discharge, skin changes)</li>
                  <li>Any symptoms that worry you or affect your quality of life</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="card">
